and expose police impunity provides a unique case study of social movements in the borderlands, especially as statistics reveal that the rates of femicide in Juárez are actually similar to other regions of Mexico. Also examining how non-governmental organizations have responded in the face of Mexican law enforcement's "normalization" of domestic violence, Staudt's study is a landmark development in the realm of global human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHomicidezMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aHuman rightszMexican-American Border Region. 0aMigrant laborzMexican-American Border Region. 0aPolice misconductzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aSexual abuse victimszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aVictims of violent crimeszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aWomen political activistszMexican-American Border Region. 0aWomenxCrimes againstzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71670440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794351/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK